{
  "text": "One of such species is Trichia papillata Adamonytė. This species was described in Lithuania in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Fruiting bodies formed during cultivation in moist chambers on the hare (Lepus sp.) and roe deer (Capreolus capreolus) dung. Information about finding of T. papillata in Taiwan was published in 2007 (liu et al., 2007) . In that study, one specimen was collected in Wenshan Botanical Gardens of National Taiwan University, and two more were obtained in moist chamber cultures on the 43rd and 74th day of incubation. In both cases, fruiting bodies formed on leaf litter and small twigs (liu et al., 2007) .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "89224923",
    "[CITATION_2]": "89224923"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "89224923": {
      "title": "Trichia papillata, a new coprophilous myxomycete species",
      "abstract": "A new species, Trichia papillata, is described on the basis of collections from Lithuania. It is characterised by angular peridial plates with a central papilla, double-crested spirals on the elaters, and yellow spore mass. T. papillata was obtained from moist chamber cultures of hare (Lepus sp.) and roe deer (Capreolus capreolus) dung collected in the southern Lithuania. The species is illustrated with SEM photographs and compared with other stalked yellow-spored Trichia species with areolate peridia."
    }
  }
}